				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/a-random-day" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1841781); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1841781&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610156387" alt="A Random Day" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1841781)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/a-random-day" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1841781); return false;" >A Random Day</a></span> <span class="odate time_1605112305 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Nov 2020 16:31</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4816303">
									

<p>&quot;Deja vu is actually people recalling amnesticized memories&quot; is a great concept. But the glacial pacing of the article means that I have to wade through paragraphs of clumsy exposition and lines like <em>&quot;All mentions of &quot;Project Immortality&quot; and other actions regarding inter-dimensional analyzing of deaths of alternate individuals are to be expunged from Foundation databases.</em>&quot; to get to that point. Then the article throws out the deja vu concept entirely to mash up alternate dimensions, antimemetics, and fake data glitching with over-the-top lines like <em>ALL TH0SE D3ATH5 F0R N.THI1NgG</em> (leetspeak should also be left in the past) to create buildup that has no mood, atmosphere, or tension. The ending is a confusing, disjointed exposition dump about evil Overseers and multiverse genocide that has zero weight or catharsis and feels utterly disjointed from the rest of the article.</p>
<p>I strongly encourage that this be rewritten again. The Overseer soul-map story needs to be thrown out entirely &#8212; it's meandering, poorly explained, disjointed, and clumsily pieced together through an exposition dump badly bolted onto the SCP format. Paul Verlaine isn't a character at all &#8212; he's a name that's dropped into the article without significance or meaning. A good rewrite of this article would explore the relationships between memory, reality and false recollections, and engage with how easy it is for a person to rewrite their own past simply because it's all filtered through memory. Maybe Paul Verlaine could be the original test subject for the Foundation's first amnestics &#8212; over time, as they amnesticize him and feed him false memories, something starts to happen so that his memories start to become everyone else's. There's a lot of different character-driven avenues to explore, and the nature of memory is an inherently rich topic to mine for horror. As it is, this piece is simply too high concept for its own good.</p>

							</div>

								
					
