			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4816427">
									

<p>The several &quot;layers&quot; of articles make it take far too long to get to the point, especially because each &quot;layer&quot; doesn't really add much and is largely repetetive, then suddenly there's a giant exposition piece at the end that exactly hits that all-too-often poorly executed cliche of &quot;note written in plain language that tells you what you just read.&quot; The core idea behind it isn't <em>terrible</em>, but certainly I've seen better executions on the theme of &quot;the foundation created an anomaly&quot; or &quot;real thing is actually an anomaly.&quot;</p>
<p>The thing about killing off 14 different universes also feels like overkill nonsense that's supposed to make you go &quot;Woaaaah that's a lot of people they killed, that sure is bad!&quot; and fails miserably. We have no connection to these universes, and killing them off right after introducing them doesn't create any emotional impact.</p>
<p>And as a less important tidbit, I can get behind the O5 council trying to make <em>themselves</em> immortal, but trying to make <em>everyone</em> immortal, <em>especially</em> through anomalous means, is not something I like. Even the end of death canon only had <em>one</em> member of the O5 council actively liking the idea due to an intense fear of dying.</p>

